'''Karakuni Shrine''' (辛国神社, からくにじんじゃ) is a Shinto shrine located in {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|ja|大阪府|12=draft}}, {{ill|Fujidera City|ja|藤井寺市|12=draft}}. It is classified as a {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|12=draft}}, and its former Rank was that of a {{ill|Murasya|ja|村社|12=draft}}.

== Worshipped deities (Saijin) ==
{{see also|{{ill|Saijin|ja|祭神|12=draft}}}}
; Main Hall
* {{ill|Nigihayahi-no-Mikoto|ja|饒速日命|12=draft}} (Nigihayahi-no-Mikoto)
* {{ill|Ameno-koyane-no-Mikoto|ja|天児屋根命|1=Ame-no-Koyane|12=draft}} (Ameno-koyane-no-Mikoto)
* {{ill|Susanoo-no-Mikoto|ja|素盞鳴命|12=draft}} (Susanoo-no-Mikoto)

; Side Hall
* {{ill|Ichikishimahime-no-Mikoto|ja|市杵島姫命|1=Ichikishimahime|12=draft}} (Ichikishimahime-no-Mikoto)
* {{ill|Hondawake-no-Mikoto|ja|品陀別命|1=Emperor Ōjin|lt=Hondawake no Mikoto|12=draft}} (Hondawake-no-Mikoto)

== History ==
The name "Karakuni" derives from a branch of the {{ill|Mononobe clan|ja|物部氏|12=draft}} that once ruled this area and produced the shamanistic figure {{ill|Karakuni Renzu|ja|辛国連|12=draft}}—a disciple of {{ill|Yaku Kogumi|ja|役小角|12=draft}}. Although the founding date is unknown, according to the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft}} in the entry for the 13th year, March of the reign of {{ill|Yuryaku Tennō|ja|雄略天皇|12=draft}}, it states that "Eka Chōno-mura was granted to Mononobe Ōren," indicating that the Mononobe clan, upon receiving these lands, enshrined their ancestor {{ill|Nigihayahi-no-Mikoto|ja|饒速日命|12=draft}}, from which Karakuni Renzu later assumed responsibility for the rites.<ref name="藤井寺1">{{Cite book|lang=ja|title=Fujidera City History|volume=Volume 1, General History, page 638|date=1997}}</ref> According to the {{ill|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|ja|日本三代実録|12=draft}}, on September 26 of the 9th year of {{ill|Jōgan|ja|貞観|12=draft}} ({{ill|867 AD|ja|867th year|12=draft}}), the shrine was listed among the government-supported shrines, and it is recorded in the {{ill|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|ja|延喜式神名帳|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|12=draft}} as a government-issued small shrine. It appears that during this period the shrine was located to the southwest of 【Emisaka】.<ref name="ミナカワ1">[http://travel-minakawa.com/2018/01/01/post-917/ Southern Kawachi’s most beautiful and long approach – Introduction to Karakuni Shrine ~ Fujidera City ~] (Accessed May 21, 2022)</ref>

In the {{ill|Meiji Period|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|12=draft}}, the shrine was renamed "Karakuni Shrine" and, in {{ill|1872 AD|ja|1872nd year|12=draft}} (Meiji 5), it was designated as a {{ill|Murasya|ja|村社|12=draft}}. In {{ill|1907 AD|ja|1907th year|12=draft}} (Meiji 40), the village shrine of Nonaka in Nonaka Village was merged, and the following year, the village shrine of Nagano in Fujidera (from the Nagano area) housed in {{ill|Katsui-dera|ja|葛井寺|1=Fujii-dera|12=draft}} was merged. As a result, {{ill|Susanoo-no-Mikoto|ja|素盞鳴命|12=draft}} of Nagano Shrine was also enshrined.<ref name="藤井寺1">{{Cite book|lang=ja|title=Fujidera City History|volume=Volume 1, General History, page 638|date=1997}}</ref><ref name="ミナカワ1">[http://travel-minakawa.com/2018/01/01/post-917/ Southern Kawachi’s most beautiful and long approach – Introduction to Karakuni Shrine ~ Fujidera City ~] (Accessed May 21, 2022)</ref> Subsequently, Nonaka Shrine was re-established atop the posterior circular part of Nonaka Miyashiro Kofun in {{ill|1950 AD|ja|1950th year|12=draft}} (Showa 25).

== Shrine facilities ==
[[File:Karakuni-jinja, Kasuga-inari-jinja.jpg|thumb|200px|Kasuga Inari Shrine]]
[[File:Karakuni-jinja, Kasuga-tenmangu.jpg|thumb|200px|Kasuga Tenmangu]]
Within the shrine grounds, there is a long approach (参道) covered in deep green foliage, which was selected in {{ill|1989 AD|ja|1989th year|12=draft}} (the first year of {{ill|Heisei|ja|平成|12=draft}}) as one of the {{ill|Osaka Midori no Hyakusen|ja|大阪みどりの百選|12=draft}}.<ref name="観光1">[http://www.fujiidera-kanko.info/spot/karakuni.html Karakuni Shrine – Fujidera City Tourism Association] (Accessed January 30, 2018)</ref> Additionally, along the approach there is a torii bearing the inscription "Nagano Shrine," which was relocated from Nagano Shrine.<ref name="藤井寺2">「Fujidera City History」, Volume 1, General History, page 635 (1997)</ref>
* Main Hall
* Haiden (worship hall)
* Kasuga {{ill|Tenmangu|ja|天満宮|12=draft}} – enshrines {{ill|Sugawara no Michizane|ja|Sugawara no Michizane|12=draft}}
* Kasuga {{ill|Inari Shrine|ja|稲荷神社|12=draft}} – enshrines {{ill|Ukano Mitama-no-Ōkami|ja|宇迦之御魂大神|12=draft}}
* Administrative Office
* A remote worship area for {{ill|Ise Jingū|ja|伊勢神宮|12=draft}}

== Festivals ==
* New Year's Festival ({{ill|January 1|ja|1月1日|12=draft}})
* Setsubun Festival (on {{ill|Setsubun|ja|節分|12=draft}})
* Spring Inari Festival (on the vernal equinox)
* Great Purification Ritual of Mizu-nazuki ({{ill|June 30|ja|6月30日|12=draft}})
* Summer Festival ({{ill|July 17|ja|7月17日|12=draft}})
* Special Festival ({{ill|October 17|ja|10月17日|12=draft}})
* Monthly Festival (on the 1st day of every month)

== Local Information ==
; Address:
* {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|ja|大阪府|12=draft}} {{ill|Fujidera City|ja|藤井寺市|12=draft}} Fujidera 1-chōme, 19-14
; Transportation:
* Nearest Station: {{ill|Kintetsu Minami-Osaka Line|ja|近鉄南大阪線|12=draft}}{{ill|Fujidera Station|ja|藤井寺駅|12=draft}}; approximately an 8‑minute walk (about 600 m to the southeast).

